observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Verify, analyze, and validate all the dormant accounts as well as secure and collate relevant documents or accounts such as financial statements, ledgers, schedules, vouchers; otherwise;


Prepare the detailed report with all the necessary documents listed in Items 7.1.f.i and 7.1.f.iii of COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 15, 2023 for the long outstanding reconciling items. The same shall be forwarded to the Head of the Agency along with a recommendation that an investigation be conducted to determine the cause of the loss of documents and identify the official or employee responsible.

We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Direct the Inventory Committee to complete a comprehensive annual physical inventory of its properties and prepare and submit the RPCPPE in accordance with Section 124 of MNGAS for LGUs Volume 1;
Direct the Inventory Committee to implement the one-time cleansing of the PPE in accordance with the procedures of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify tangible items with acquisition cost of less than ₱50,000.00 that were initially classified as PPE to semi-expendable properties and their respective accumulated depreciation to be closed in the books of accounts in accordance with Item Nos. 4.2 and 4.3 of COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022; and
Revisit the computations of Depreciation Expense and Accumulated Depreciation, as well as the allocation of salvage values to some of the PPE items, to ensure the accuracy of their net book values
We also recommended and the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate agreed to prepare their respective PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards using the prescribed formats, and conduct reconciliation of the PPEs reported in the physical count with the balances in the accounting and property records, to establish the correct and reliable balance of the PPE accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant:
Verify and analyze all the dormant receivable accounts, secure relevant documents for each, and establish their validity;
Gather and prepare the necessary documents for writing off of dormant receivable accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005, dated December 19, 2016;
Establish a provision for losses or an Allowance for Impairment to receivable accounts whose degree of collectability is uncertain to ensure the fair presentation of the account balance; and
Strengthen controls over the monitoring of receivable accounts and take necessary steps to collect them immediately.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the Office of the General Services to:
a. Insure with the GSIS-GIF the City’s properties against any insurable risk and pay the premiums thereon, pursuant to RA No. 656;
b. Prepare the PIF as required under Paragraph 5.1.e of COA Circular No. 2018-002;
c. Submit the consolidated PIF to the Audit Team leader per Paragraph 5.1.e of the same Circular.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the City Accountant:
a. to send within ten (10) days before the expiration of the prescribed period a written reminder, signed by the Mayor or his duly authorized representative, to the officials and employees concerned to settle their cash advances;
b. not to sign claims for additional cash advance until the previous cash advance is settled;
c. to cause the immediate withholding of salaries and claims of officers and employees who failed to settle their cash advances within the prescribed period after being sent notice and demand;
d. to furnish all department head listings of all unliquidated cash advances of employees under their charge to enhance the liquidation efforts.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the City Engineer to:
a. Determine the unperformed portion of the project at the time of the expiration of the contract which was on June 27, 2018 (first revised completion date of May 28, 2018 plus 30 calendar days extension granted on July 9, 2018);
b. Recompute the liquidated damages for the project, including the number of delays when there was no approved extension granted, and bill and collect the amount from the contractor.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the Office of the City Accountant to:
a. reconcile its records on the amounts withheld and remitted and remit immediately to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth the unremitted amounts withheld from employees;
b. adopt monitoring measures in the withholding and prompt remittance of amounts due to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and Philhealth;
c. update the accounting records monthly in order to determine the exact amount to be remitted to avoid penalties and surcharges.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the inventory committee to:

Summarize the result of the physical inventory count per PPE account to come up with the complete list of PPEs;

Reconcile the physical count with the records maintained by the Supply Officer/Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant;

Submit the RPCPPE containing the complete list of PPEs with technical descriptions and specifications in conformity with the provisions of Chapter 7 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGU, Volume I.  

We further recommended that the OIC - Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer/Municipal Treasurer undertake immediate reconciliation of the PPE per physical inventory conducted as against the property ledger cards and property cards and effect adjustments, if any, to reflect the correct balances of PPE accounts as reflected in the financial statements.

We recommended that the inventory committee:

